SIMPLE: clutter
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Clutter
<hw>Clut"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. W.
<ets>cludair</ets> heap, pile, <ets>cludeirio</ets> to heap.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A confused collection; hence, confusion; disorder;
<as>as, the room is in a <ex>clutter</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He saw what a <qex>clutter</qex> there was with huge, overgrown
pots, pans, and spits.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Clatter; confused noise.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clutter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Clutter
<hw>Clut"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Cluttered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Cluttering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To crowd together in disorder;
to fill or cover with things in disorder; to throw into disorder; to
disarrange; <as>as, to <ex>clutter</ex> a room</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clutter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Clutter
<hw>Clut"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a confused noise; to
bustle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It [the goose] <qex>cluttered</qex> here, it chuckled there.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clutter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Clutter
<hw>Clut"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Clod</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To clot or coagulate, as blood.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Clydesdale</ent>⟦br⟧
